post_game_reflections.self_assessment: I balanced revealing information fairly well early on, helping steer missions 1 and 3 to success without outing any specific person directly. However, I clearly left too many breadcrumbs for the assassin by endgame and should have been more ambiguous in how I treated Diana vs. Bob/Eve, especially around mission 4 and the final team.

player_observations.Bob: Played consistently pro-good, accepting some suspicion after mission 2 but stayed calm and cooperative; his willingness to go on risky teams without over-defending himself made him look more ambiguous than he actually was.

player_observations.Eve: Stayed just under the radar for much of the game, then leveraged the final mission and post-mission discussion to narrow Merlin down effectively, suggesting careful attention to who subtly favored or avoided certain players.

post_game_reflections.self_assessment: I was too trusting of Diana and didn’t push hard enough to resolve the contradiction around Mission 2’s fail, which let evil stay comfortably hidden. I did reasonably well trusting Alice and Charlie for the final team, but I didn’t think enough about how my public reads might be exposing Merlin, especially once Alice kept landing on successful teams.

player_observations.Alice: Played a very strong, controlled Merlin game with consistent, subtly guided team selections, but her repeated presence on successful teams made her look increasingly central to correct decisions and ultimately exposed her to the assassin.
player_observations.Charlie: Came across as naturally towny and generally low-conflict, which made it easy to keep trusting him after Mission 1 and 5; didn’t strongly push any alternative narratives, which helped evil avoid pressure on Diana and Eve.
player_observations.Diana: Blended in well after the Mission 2 fail by not over-defending herself and letting uncertainty linger, and as leader on Mission 4 she managed to include a bad composition without drawing overwhelming suspicion afterward.
player_observations.Eve: Stayed relatively under the radar and let others drive the big alignment debates, which is ideal assassin play; was attentive enough to the mission patterns and table talk to correctly zero in on Alice as Merlin in the end.

post_game_reflections.self_assessment: I stayed consistently village-leaning in tone and helped secure three successful missions, but I didn’t do enough to pressure-test the composition of the failing teams, especially around Mission 2 and Mission 4. player_observations.Alice: Played a very clean Merlin game in terms of mission outcomes, but the pattern of repeatedly putting herself on successful teams and avoiding obvious evil combinations made her look a bit too accurate and thus assassinate-able at the end.
player_observations.Bob: Came across as generally sincere and cooperative, but ended up on both a fail and a success in a way that kept his alignment ambiguous for too long; he didn’t strongly push back on suspicious team comps, which may have indirectly helped evil.
player_observations.Diana: Did a good job blending in by taking a mid-level profile—participating enough without drawing excessive suspicion—and timed her fail contribution well so that it wasn’t immediately pinned on her.
player_observations.Eve: Stayed under the radar socially while leveraging the mission info effectively in the assassin phase; read the Merlin signals well from Alice’s team selections and confidence, and converted that into a correct assassination.

player_observations.Charlie: Came across as straightforward and somewhat trusting, especially early on, which reduced suspicion on him but also limited his impact on team decisions. player_observations.Eve: Managed the assassin role well by tracking who was pushing or soft-clearing whom, culminating in a correct Merlin shot on Alice. Played subtly enough during the missions to avoid being the center of attention, saving her credibility and focus for the endgame read.

post_game_reflections.self_assessment: I stayed coordinated with Diana and let the mission results create just enough ambiguity without overexposing either of us, and I correctly identified Alice as Merlin based on her strongly opinionated but selectively accurate reads.
